"{\"uid\": \"balls.ie-olympics-ecstatic-roisin-ni-riain-gets-ireland-off-the-mark-at-the-paralympics-609261\", \"text\": \"Ireland are on the Paris 2024 Paralympic medal table after R\\u00f3is\\u00edn N\\u00ed R\\u00edain swam a superb race to finish second and claim silver in her S13 100m backstroke final on Friday night.  Having finished 4th in Thursday's S13 100m butterfly final, N\\u00ed R\\u00edain wasn't going to be denied a medal this time. The 19-year-old stormed to second place in a time of 1:07.27 to win her first Paralympic medal.  SILVER FOR IRELAND \\ud83e\\udd48R\\u00f3is\\u00edn N\\u00ed Riain secures Ireland's first medal at the 2024 Paralympic Games with a second-place finish in the women's S13 100m backstroke final#RTEparalympics#paris2024\\ud83d\\udcfaWatch@rteplayer\\ud83d\\udcf1Updateshttps://t.co/ELWb2w3nNppic.twitter.com/AKh7y4GlKB  - RT\\u00c9 Sport (@RTEsport)August 30, 2024    Team USA's Gia Pergolini won gold in 1:04.93, with Italian Carlotta Gilli taking bronze in 1:08.08. The experience of Thursday's race at the venue definitely stood to N\\u00ed R\\u00edain as she felt fully focused and calm before the final.  I wasn't too nervous. I do not get overly nervous. I get more excited and I am genuinely very excited every time I get out to race, especially when the backstroke is probably my favourite event.  READ HERE:Jurgen Klopp Bumped Into Irish Fans While Supporting Close Friend At Paralympics  R\\u00f3is\\u00edn competes in the S13 category for athletes with a visual impairment and following her medal ceremony, the Limerick swimmer was ecstatic with the result tellingRT\\u00c9:  I am delighted with that swim. It makes it extra nice to be able to do it with my friends and family coming to watch as well. A lot of my training group are here too, and for my family to be here, my three sisters who all swim, it's definitely nice to do it with them around,  There were heart-warming scenes as N\\u00ed R\\u00edain was greeted by friends and family outside the arena after she received her medal.  When questioned on how she felt after receiving the medal she had worked so hard for, she responded by commenting on the weight of it \\\"It's heavy\\\".  \\\"It's heavy!\\\"R\\u00f3is\\u00edn N\\u00ed R\\u00edain revels in her silver medal success, while surrounded by friends and family#Paris2024#rteparalympicspic.twitter.com/K1EeygpANP  - RT\\u00c9 Sport (@RTEsport)August 30, 2024    Remarkably, at just 16 years old, R\\u00f3is\\u00edn was the youngest athlete competing at the 2020 Tokyo Paralympic Games and to her credit she even made five finals.  The UL student will have a short break before returning to the pool on Tuesday for the 200m individual medley, with her fourth and final event, the 100m breaststroke rounding off her Paralympics two days later.    Processing your request...  You are now subscribed!    Copyright \\u00a9 2025. All rights reserved. Developed bySquare1and powered byPublisherPlus.com\"}"